Here's how it works:

Line 1-3: SELECT picks the columns we want to see—id, name, and rating.

Line 4: FROM products tells SQL which table to pull data from.

Line 5: ORDER BY rating DESC sorts products by rating from highest to lowest.

Line 6: LIMIT 10 restricts the results to exactly 10 rows—giving us the top 10.

Ex:
SELECT category
FROM products;
Here's how the code works:

DISTINCT is placed immediately after SELECT and tells SQL to show only unique values from the category column. It automatically removes all duplicates.

SELECT DISTINCT category
FROM products;

EX: 
SELECT DISTINCT column_name
FROM table_name;

You can write SQL keywords in uppercase or lowercase—both work. But the convention is to use uppercase (like SELECT, DISTINCT, FROM) because it makes keywords easier to distinguish from table and column names.

Exercisie:
Write a query to find all the unique cities where our customers live. The table is called customers.

SELECT DISTINCT city
FROM  customers

Ex:
When we get the unique categories, the result column is labeled category. But we can give it a more descriptive name like unique_categories to make our output clearer and more professional.

SELECT DISTINCT category AS unique_categories
FROM products;

unique_categories instead of just category—much more descriptive!

Here's how it works:

AS assigns a new display name to the column that comes before it
The alias appears in your results header but doesn't change the actual column name in the database
You place AS right after the column name, followed by your chosen alias

The pattern is:
SELECT column_1 AS alias_name
FROM table_1;

Now, when creating aliases, you want to follow some best practices:

1. Descriptive: Clearly indicate what the data represents

2. Valid: Use only letters, numbers, and underscores

3. Readable: Use lowercase with underscores between words—this is called snake_case convention (like unique_categories)

These practices make your queries professional and easy to understand. 

Ex:
SELECT city AS customer_cities
FROM customers

To connect to a database, you'll need these details:

Server address: Where the database lives (URL or IP address)
Username: Your account name
Password: Your account password
Database name: Which specific database to use
When you start working at an organization, you'll get these connection details from your database administrator or IT team.

